[4]
Date: 14 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hong Kong Department of Health
<http://www.info.gov.hk/dh/new/2003/03-06-10e.htm>
Situation report on Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome
June 14, 2003
The following is jointly issued by the Department of Health and the
Hospital Authority:
No new confirmed case of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) was
reported today (June 14), marking the third consecutive day of zero
infection in Hong Kong. It is also the 30th day in a row on which the
number of case has fallen below five since May 16.
The number of patients recovered and discharged from hospital
continues to rise to 1382. Of them, two were discharged today.
The number of SARS patients in intensive care unit is 16. These cases
are part of the 53 cases under treatment in hospitals. Most of the
patients are showing positive responses to the treatment protocol. In
addition, 26 are recovering patients in convalescence and in
preparation for discharge.
A 69-year-old woman who has a history of chronic disease died in
Alice Ho Miu Ling Nethersole Hospital, bringing to 294 the total
number of deaths relating to SARS.
Meanwhile, temperature checks for all passengers at the airport,
ports and border points continue to be implemented to watch for
travellers displaying symptoms of SARS. In addition, all incoming
travellers are required to complete a health declaration. Four
passengers were screened out during temperature checks at these
points yesterday. After undergoing further medical checks, all four
were however cleared of SARS symptoms.
The cumulative total of persons covered by home confinement remains
at 1 262 (from 493 households). Thanks to the co-operation of the
confinees and members of the community, no new warning letter has
been issued since May 16 and the scheme is running smoothly.
The cumulative figure for patients who have been admitted to public
hospitals with SARS since March 12 is as follows:
Cumulative no. cases/ total no. discharged patients/ total no. deaths
(change in past 24 hours presented in parentheses, minus used for decrease)
