[6]
Date: 13 Jun 2003
From: Henry L. Niman Ph.D. <henry_niman@hms.harvard.edu>
Source: Associated Press [edited]

Health officials say co-worker of US SARS patient dies of pneumonia
----------------------------------------------
A co-worker of the man with the first confirmed case of SARS in North
Carolina died Friday of heart failure and pneumonia, state health
officials said.
The 45-year-old man was one of 2 pneumonia victims who worked in the same
building as the SARS patient. In preliminary tests, both showed no signs of
having SARS, but more thorough examinations were pending, health officials
said.
The SARS patient and the dead man, had overlapping work hours on 3 successive
days last month in the same building at the University of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill.
The SARS patient showed no symptoms at the time, and state health director
Leah Devlin said there are no reported cases anywhere in the world in which a
co-worker outside a medical setting passed the disease to a colleague.
The man who died had suffered a chronic cough for weeks and his condition
suddenly deteriorated Monday, the News & Observer reported Friday. State
epidemiologist Dr. Jeffrey Engel would only say Friday that they were still
investigating the background of his condition.
The 2nd pneumonia patient was being monitored at home after being treated
at Duke University Medical Center.
"Follow-up testing is being conducted to see if we can completely rule out the
possibility of SARS in both cases," Devlin said.
["Very peliminary" tests from CDC] showed both men negative for SARS; the
same kind of test, involving swabs from the nose or the back of the throat,
confirmed the diagnosis of SARS in the first man.
"Right now we're calling it definitely heading down the right track," Engel
said. "But you cannot rule out a case of SARS until several days after the
initial onset of illness."
Blood test results from the CDC on the 2 pneumonia patients could be back as
early as Monday. Engel said the most conclusive test can only be done 21 to 28
days after onset of symptoms.
The SARS patient and the dead man had overlapping work times May 21-23 in the
Giles F. Horney Building, which houses facilities services offices off the
university's main campus. A spokeswoman for the state Department of Health and
Human Services, Carol Schriber, said she did not know how long the men were in
the same building. "The disease investigation so far has not shown close
personal contact between the two people," Schriber said.
The university has offered health screenings to 500 employees who worked in
the building or for the energy services department, as well as their immediate
family members. As of Friday afternoon, 35 people had been examined and none
showed symptoms related to SARS.
The SARS patient, an Orange County resident, could be released from isolation
at home on Saturday -- 10 days after his last symptom disappeared, state
health officials said.
Test results from the CDC confirmed the Orange County man's diagnosis Monday,
making him the 8th confirmed case of SARS in the United States. He
apparently contracted SARS after encountering an infected person during a
visit to a Toronto geriatric rehabilitation center. None of his family has
shown any symptoms. State health officials quarantined 12 people at an Orange
County doctor's office, 3 from a UNC-CH hospital and 2 family members of the
SARS patient. The quarantine was to end Saturday.
Also, 9 members of the staff at Duke University Medical Center and 2 at
Western Wake Medical Center were being monitored for symptoms. 4 health
care workers at Western Wake were on furlough because they had close exposure
to the man who died, though they did not show any symptoms of SARS.
[Byline: Jay Cohen]
--
Henry L Niman, PhD
Instructor in Surgery (Bioengineering)
Harvard Medical School
<henry_niman@hms.harvard.edu>
[As of yesterday, the number of SARS cases worldwide stood at 8454, with only
10 new cases from around the world. The reassignment of Toronto to category
C (disease occurring in those not previously known to have had contact with a
SARS patient) is indicative of the seriousness with which WHO views the
situation in that area. If the North Carolina contact of the SARS case in
that state is confirmed to have had SARS, it will represent the first U.S.
death from this disease. - Mod.LM]
